DPPchain Specification v0.1 — Technical Foundation
We stand for free, unmanipulated data.
This document covers the technical standards DPPchain builds on. For architecture and principles see SPEC.md. For real-world examples see SPEC2.md.
The format already exists
DPPchain does not invent a new data format. The format already exists, is open, and is being standardized at the international level. DPPchain builds on what is already there.
Three open standards form the foundation:
JSON-LD
JSON-LD (JSON for Linked Data) is the data format DPP records are built on.
It is human-readable and machine-readable simultaneously. A developer can read it directly like source code. An AI agent can parse it instantly. A regulator can audit it without special tools.
This is exactly the property described in SPEC.md — the system works without AI, AI only makes it faster.
A DPP record in JSON-LD looks like this:
{
  "type": ["DigitalProductPassport", "VerifiableCredential"],
  "id": "https://example-company.com/credentials/2a423366",
  "issuer": {
    "id": "did:web:identifiers.example-company.com:12345",
    "name": "Example Company"
  },
  "validFrom": "2025-06-15T12:00:00Z",
  "validUntil": "2035-03-15T12:00:00Z",
  "credentialSubject": {
    "type": ["ProductPassport"],
    "product": {
      "id": "https://example.com/id/9520123456788",
      "registeredId": "9520123456788",
      "countryOfProduction": "PL",
      "productionDate": "2025-04-25",
      "characteristics": {}
    }
  }
}
Every field is typed. Every value is verifiable. Every record has an issuer with legal identity behind it.
GS1 Digital Link
GS1 Digital Link is the identifier system. Think of it as ISBN for books — but for every physical product in the world.
Every product gets a unique identifier. That identifier resolves to a URL. That URL returns the JSON-LD record with full product data.
Scan a QR code on a product — get the full DPP record. No app required. No proprietary system. Standard HTTP request.
QR code on product
     ↓
GS1 Digital Link identifier
     ↓
HTTP GET request
     ↓
JSON-LD DPP record with full verified data
This is the access layer. DPPchain queries it exactly like a browser queries a website — except instead of HTML for humans it gets JSON-LD for machines.
UNTP — UN Transparency Protocol
UNTP is the international specification for Digital Product Passports developed under the UN Centre for Trade Facilitation and Electronic Business (UN/CEFACT).
It defines the full schema — what fields a DPP must contain, how conformity claims are structured, how supply chain events are recorded, how credentials are verified.
Version 0.6.0 is available now for pilot testing. Version 1.0 stable release is due mid-2025.
The schema is public and available at:
https://uncefact.github.io/spec-untp/docs/specification/DigitalProductPassport/
DPPchain implements UNTP as its primary data schema. Any DPP issued according to UNTP is readable by DPPchain without additional translation.
How DPPchain sits on top of these standards
User (plain language query)
          ↓
DPPchain AI layer
(translates intent to structured query parameters)
          ↓
DPPchain protocol layer
(constructs UNTP-compliant query)
          ↓
GS1 Digital Link registry
(resolves product identifier to data endpoint)
          ↓
JSON-LD DPP record
(verified data with legal accountability)
          ↓
DPPchain verification layer
(cross-checks sources, flags inconsistencies)
          ↓
DPPchain AI layer
(translates structured result to plain language)
          ↓
User (verified answer with full audit trail)
The AI layer exists only at the top and bottom — translating human language to machine parameters and back. Everything in the middle is open standards that work without AI.
A developer who wants to query DPP data directly can do so without DPPchain and without AI. DPPchain makes it accessible to everyone else.
Regulatory timeline
DPP is not a future concept. The legal framework is in place and implementation is underway.
July 2024 — ESPR (Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation EU 2024/1781) entered into force. Legal foundation established for DPP across all product categories.
February 2027 — Battery passport mandatory. First product category with full DPP requirement. Over 100 data attributes including material composition, carbon footprint by lifecycle stage, recycled content, and performance data.
2027-2028 — Textiles, furniture, iron, steel, aluminium, energy-related products. First delegated acts defining specific DPP requirements for these categories expected from Q4 2025.
2030 — Construction products mandatory under CPR (Construction Products Regulation EU 2024/1305).
Mid-term review 2028 — Potential expansion to chemicals, footwear, and additional categories.
What this means for DPPchain development
DPPchain does not need to wait for DPP to be mandatory. The UNTP schema is available now. Pilot implementations exist now. The data format is stable enough to build on.
The battery category provides the first live implementation target. Battery DPP data will be mandatory from February 2027 — but companies are building systems now. DPPchain can implement battery passport queries in 2025-2026 against pilot data, before mandatory rollout.
Textiles follow. Then construction. Each new mandatory category brings more verified data into the system automatically — without DPPchain needing to do anything except support the standard it already implements.
This is the compounding effect of building on a regulatory standard. Every new product category that enters DPP compliance becomes queryable through DPPchain on day one.
Supply chain inheritance — technical implementation
As described in SPEC.md, products inherit DPP data from their input materials. This is technically implemented through UNTP's supply chain event model.
A manufacturer declares:
{
  "inputProducts": [
    {
      "productId": "https://supplier.com/id/RAW-COTTON-00112",
      "dppReference": "https://supplier.com/credentials/dpp-00112",
      "quantity": "500kg"
    },
    {
      "productId": "https://dye-supplier.com/id/DYE-00089",
      "dppReference": "https://dye-supplier.com/credentials/dpp-00089",
      "quantity": "2kg"
    }
  ],
  "outputProduct": {
    "productId": "https://manufacturer.com/id/TSHIRT-00441",
    "dppReference": "https://manufacturer.com/credentials/dpp-00441"
  }
}
Each input product reference points to a verified DPP record. The output product inherits verified data from all inputs. The chain is traceable from finished product back to raw material — every link verified, every link with legal accountability behind it.
A small manufacturer who sources certified materials does not start from zero. They reference existing verified records. Their product inherits the verification. The technical burden is declaring what they used — not re-verifying what suppliers already verified.
